i made this because i wanted a simple agent harness that didn't stop until a long-horizon task was completed. everything i tried was either a huge framework or a one-shot script that gave up after one reply. i wanted something small, something that would just keep going.

tenacity-harness takes one task and loops on it. each tick it reads who it is, what it's working on, what it remembers, and what i whispered to it, then asks a local ollama model what to do next. it runs shell commands, updates its own memory, and keeps ticking. it only stops when the model wraps a short summary in a done block, or when it hits max ticks as a safety net.

soul.md is who it is. task.md is the long-horizon thing you want done. memory.md is its scratchpad across ticks. heartbeat.md is what i say to it each tick. log.txt is every thought and action, append-only.

four fenced blocks drive everything. sh runs a shell command. memory overwrites memory.md. note appends a timestamped line to memory.md. done ends the harness.

you need node 20 and ollama. pull a small model, then:

  node src/index.js "investigate the slow test in auth and fix it"

or write task.md yourself and just run node src/index.js. tune it with TENACITY_MODEL, TENACITY_MAX_TICKS, TENACITY_TICK_DELAY_MS, TENACITY_CMD_TIMEOUT_MS, and OLLAMA_URL.

one thing. a sh block runs with whatever permissions you start this with, so keep soul.md honest, don't run it as root, and read the log. it's alone down there and it's trying its best to finish what you asked.
